<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10144a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10144a">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10144a"> 144(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hedging / temporiser / time serve / dog = lion</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In speaking&mdash;say&mdash;this slippery native can only twist in and out of an idea precisely as he twists along his path; &ldquo;Going, I went, and speaking, I spoke, and doing, I did,&rdquo; being the average formula of your wriggly black. An adjacent <mark>lion is called a &ldquo;dog,&rdquo;</mark> and a friend asking a friend to drink beer is vaguely invited to drink &ldquo;water.&rdquo; Hence the famous fact that our son of Ham will never come straight to the point, but <mark>hedges and temporises</mark>&mdash;&ldquo;meandering to the point&rdquo; he calls it. <small> Daniel Crawford, <a name="DCTB" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DCTB"><cite title="source">Thinking Black</cite></a> (1912) 115</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c01072a" href="c01all.htm#c01072a">VI.C.01:072(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
